==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Harbinger
<hw>Har"bin*ger</hw> <pr>(h⟦add⟧r"b⟦icr⟧n*j⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[OE. <ets>herbergeour</ets>, OF. <ets>herbergeor</ets> one who
provides lodging, fr. <ets>herbergier</ets> to provide lodging, F.
<ets>h⟦eacute⟧berger</ets>, OF. <ets>herberge</ets> lodging, inn, F.
<ets>auberge</ets>; of German origin. See <er>Harbor</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>One who provides lodgings; especially, the officer of
the English royal household who formerly preceded the court when
traveling, to provide and prepare lodgings.</def>
<rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A forerunner; a precursor; a messenger.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I knew by these <qex>harbingers</qex> who were coming.</q>
<rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Harbinger</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Harbinger
<hw>Har"bin*ger</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Harbingered</conjf> <pr>(h⟦add⟧r"b⟦icr⟧n*j⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p.
pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Harbingering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To usher
in; to be a harbinger of.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Thus did the star of religious
freedom <xex>harbinger</xex> the day.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Bancroft.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Harbor</ent>⟦br⟧
